# MyDailyNews

A compact, local-first daily news briefing pipeline inspired by Horizon.

Horizon attribution:

- Project: https://github.com/Thysrael/Horizon
- License: MIT
- What we borrowed conceptually: staged orchestration, normalized content items, RSS-first discovery, AI scoring, semantic dedupe, enrichment, and final daily summary generation.
- What we intentionally left out: social media scrapers, Apify/Twitter, DuckDuckGo browsing, email/webhooks, GitHub Pages publishing, and feedback-based preference mutation.


## Pipeline

```text
load config and long-term memory
  -> create orchestrator
  -> fetch headline candidates from configured RSS sources
  -> ask local LLM to score and dedupe headline/snippet candidates
  -> keep items above cutoff
  -> fetch full article HTML only for selected items
  -> extract readable text with trafilatura
  -> ask local LLM whether enrichment is needed
  -> if needed: retrieve Wikipedia summary + Google News RSS results from last month
  -> ask local LLM to create a machine-readable daily brief
  -> write Markdown and JSON outputs
```


## Why This Is Mobile-Friendly Later

The expensive work is delayed until after headline triage. A weaker phone model can score short headline/snippet batches first, then read only a small number of full articles. The final JSON output is also suitable for a future mobile renderer or text-to-speech pipeline.


## Current Modules

- `main.py`: thin CLI.
- `mydailynews/config.py`: loads app config and long-term user memory.
- `mydailynews/models.py`: shared data models.
- `mydailynews/orchestrator.py`: Horizon-style staged pipeline.
- `mydailynews/scrapers/rss.py`: RSS headline discovery.
- `mydailynews/ai/headline_analyzer.py`: local LLM scoring and dedupe.
- `mydailynews/retrieval/article.py`: full article extraction.
- `mydailynews/enrichment.py`: decides whether to enrich and retrieves context.
- `mydailynews/retrieval/wikipedia.py`: Wikipedia context.
- `mydailynews/retrieval/past_news.py`: last-month Google News RSS context.
- `mydailynews/brief.py`: final JSON brief generation.
- `mydailynews/output.py`: Markdown and JSON writing.


## Quick Start

```powershell
cd d:\Project\MyDailyNews
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
pip install -r requirements.txt
copy config.example.json config.json
python main.py --config config.json
```

For a lighter first run:

```powershell
python main.py --config config.json --no-enrichment
```


## Config Memory

Long-term memory is currently explicit and configurable in `config.json`:

```json
{
  "user_memory": {
    "preferred_topics": ["AI", "technology policy", "global economy"],
    "avoided_topics": ["celebrity gossip"],
    "preferred_sources": ["BBC World", "NPR"],
    "briefing_style": "Concise, explanatory, practical, and skeptical of hype.",
    "custom_instructions": "Include some major stories outside my usual interests."
  }
}
```

There is no thumbs up/down learning in this version. The code is structured so feedback can later update this memory safely.


## Outputs

Each run writes:

- `output/YYYY-MM-DD_brief.md`: readable daily brief.
- `output/YYYY-MM-DD_brief.json`: machine-readable brief for future mobile/TTS use.

The JSON schema includes:

- `metadata`
- `title`
- `lead`
- `sections`
- `articles`
- `major_headlines`


## Future Hooks

Planned features have natural module homes:

- Thumbs up/down feedback: add a memory updater beside `config.py`.
- LLM preference management: add a preference manager that rewrites/patches `user_memory`.
- Text-to-speech: consume `output/*_brief.json`.
- Better enrichment: expand `enrichment.py` with richer source-specific retrievers.
- Mobile deployment: swap `mydailynews/ai/client.py` from Ollama to an Android inference runtime.
